ent efforts. Drawing on more than two years of close-knit discussions convened by Jeffrey D. Sachs and Marcelo Sánchez Sorondo, it offers an extensive and inclusive vision of how to promote human flourishing. The book features theological, philosophical, and ethical deliberations of great diversity and depth on the challenges of sustainable development, addressing questions of poverty, environmental justice, peace, conflict, and the future of work. It includes consensus statements on the moral imperatives of sustainable development, introductions to seven major religious traditions and their conceptions of the common good, and thematic reflections. Wide-ranging and urgent, this book represents a major contribution to interreligious dialogue and to the articulation of a shared global ethics.The book features a foreword by Pope Francis and Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh  aEthics in Action.  aPope Francis.  aReligions for Peace.  aSustainable Development Goals.  aclimate change.  acomparative religion.  aenvironmental justice.  aethics.  apoverty.  areligious studies.  asustainability.  asustainable development.  athe future of work.1 aAdamakis, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnett, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnett, Anthony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAppleby, R. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartholomew, Ecumenical Patriarch, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Jermyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Christina Lee, econtributor.4c